post_text:
March 17, 2020

Please understand that Governor Wolf's 180 Day remark was in reference to PA State Code of Education. School days are permitted and could extend well into the month of June, but not past June 30th. His remarks are in reference to any days that cannot be made up by June 30th. This just does not pertain to Blacklick Valley but will apply to all districts within the Commonwealth!! We understand this is complicated and does impact family vacations, including our own. At this time our District is strictly following the guidelines of the State Department of Education. More information will follow in a formal letter sent to all families within the district! Thank you for your patience and understanding through this ever changing situation!



Sincerely,

William P. Kanich

Superintendent
Blacklick Valley School District

post_text:
March 17, 2020

Blacklick Valley Families:

To assist our community with the closures, Blacklick Valley will be providing grab-and-go style breakfast and lunch to all students of our district up to the age of 18. These meals will be provided Monday thru Friday from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m beginning Wednesday March 18th and running the entire time the schools are closed. The site of the pick-up will be in front of the Elementary Center and in front of the High School. This will run like a drive thru with cars pulling up to the curb and the breakfast/lunch being brought out to the cars.

The health and well-being of our community is extremely important to us and we will continue to assist you and keep you updated in this very unprecedented and trying time. If you have any questions regarding the lunch program please contact Dan Palko at 749-9211 ext. 233 or via e-mail at dpalko@bvsd.k12.pa.us. Thank you.



Sincerely,

William P. Kanich

Superintendent
Blacklick Valley School District

After school tutoring (AST) will begin this week. We are trying a new method for tutoring in which we will have tutoring for two weeks and then take a 1 week break. Students in grades 7 & 8 who are failing any course are assigned to attend. 9th graders who are failing 2 or more courses are assigned. As always, once you are passing your classes you can be excused from AST - see Mr. Havener
#bvjshsprincipal

Haley Rhine is an Early Childhood Teacher Education student from Blacklick Valley High School. This is her first year in the class. Haley‚Äôs favorite project in class has been creating lesson plans and teaching in the Head Start classrooms. She said she loves when the children learn something new. In the future, Haley said she would like to attend IUP and major in Early Childhood Education with a minor in Communications and would like to become a teacher. Haley said her vo-tech class is preparing her for her future career now. She said, ‚ÄúThis class is very hands-on and helps give you practice for any future career.‚Äù
